🚀 Optimized Approach: SPF Sieve (Best Way)

Instead of doing O(N√N) factorization, we use:

✅ Smallest Prime Factor (SPF) Sieve
Time: O(N log log N)

🧠 Idea

We precompute:

spf[i] = smallest prime factor of i

Then for each number:

Count distinct primes using spf
Get smallest prime in O(1)
⚙️ Step 1: Build SPF Sieve
vector<int> spf(1e6 + 1);

void build_spf() {
    for(int i = 1; i <= 1e6; i++) spf[i] = i;

    for(int i = 2; i * i <= 1e6; i++) {
        if(spf[i] == i) { // prime
            for(int j = i * i; j <= 1e6; j += i) {
                if(spf[j] == j)
                    spf[j] = i;
            }
        }
    }
}
⚙️ Step 2: Build Helper using SPF

Now we compute:

helper[i] = {multi-prime?, smallest prime}
vector<pair<bool,int>> helper(1e6 + 1);

void build_helper() {
    for(int i = 1; i <= 1e6; i++) {
        int x = i;
        int cnt = 0;
        int last = -1;

        while(x > 1) {
            int p = spf[x];
            if(p != last) {
                cnt++;
                if(cnt == 1) helper[i].second = p;
                last = p;
            }
            x /= p;
        }

        helper[i].first = (cnt > 1);
        if(cnt == 0) helper[i].second = i; // for i = 1
    }
}
⚡ Why this is better
Old approach:
O(N * sqrt(N))  ❌ slow
SPF approach:
O(N log log N)  ✅ fast

👉 Much safer for contests

🔥 Full Optimized Flow
build_spf();
build_helper();

Then your solve() remains SAME ✅

🧠 Key Insight

Using SPF:

Factorization becomes:
while(x > 1) x /= spf[x];

👉 Each step reduces x quickly
👉 Total complexity per number: ~log(n)

⚠️ Common Mistakes
❌ Forgetting to avoid duplicate primes
❌ Not tracking last
❌ Counting same prime multiple times
